---
import { getRelativeLocaleUrl } from "astro:i18n";
import Layout from "@/layouts/Layout.astro";
import Header from "@/components/Header.astro";
import Breadcrumb from "@/components/Breadcrumb.astro";
import Main from "@/components/Main.astro";
import Footer from "@/components/Footer.astro";
import config from "@/config";

const locale = Astro.currentLocale ?? config.site.lang;

const PLAYBOOK_BASE =
  "https://wenhaoyu-bryan.github.io/AI-PM-Operating-Playbook/en/workbench/";
---

<Layout
  title={`Harness Engineering | ${config.site.title}`}
  description="Designing the context, tools, constraints, tests, and feedback systems that guide AI coding agents — rather than writing code yourself."
>
  <Header />
  <Breadcrumb />

  <Main
    pageTitle="Harness Engineering for AI-Assisted Product Delivery"
    class="app-prose"
  >
    <p class="text-muted-foreground text-lg">
      Harness Engineering means designing the environment around an AI coding
      agent — the context it receives, the tools it can use, the boundaries it
      must respect, and the feedback it gets — rather than writing code
      yourself. The agent generates code. The harness makes sure it generates
      the right code.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">Model vs. Agent Loop vs. Harness</h2>
    <p>
      These three layers are easy to confuse, and confusing them leads to poor
      outcomes.
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-3">
      <li>
        <strong>The model</strong> generates text and code. It is a general-purpose
        reasoning engine. You do not control its internal weights; you control what
        you put in front of it.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The agent loop</strong> decides what to do next: read a file, run
        a test, edit code, ask for clarification. Frameworks like Claude Code or Cursor
        implement this loop. You configure it, but you do not usually write it from
        scratch.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The harness</strong> defines the environment the agent operates in:
        what it sees, what it can touch, what rules it must follow, and how it learns
        whether its output was good. This is the layer you design.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">
      Most frustration with AI coding agents comes from neglecting the harness.
      A good model in a bad harness produces unreliable results.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-8 text-xl font-semibold">Context</h2>
    <p>
      Context is the information the agent receives before and during a task.
      This includes project structure, coding conventions, existing patterns,
      domain terminology, and the specific goal of the current request.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      <strong>What the PM defines:</strong> which parts of the product landscape matter
      for this task. Which user stories are relevant. What business rules constrain
      the solution. What existing code or documentation the agent should read before
      starting. A CLAUDE.md file, project README, or a structured handoff document
      are all mechanisms for injecting context.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Tools</h2>
    <p>
      Tools are the actions available to the agent: reading and writing files,
      running commands, calling APIs, executing tests. Every tool is a
      capability and a risk. An agent with unrestricted file write access and
      shell access can build things fast — and break things fast.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      <strong>What the PM defines:</strong> the scope of tool access needed for the
      task. Does the agent need to modify the database schema, or only the frontend?
      Should it run tests, or only generate code? Scoping tool access is not a technical
      detail — it is a product safety decision.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Constraints</h2>
    <p>
      Constraints are the rules the agent must not violate. Security policies,
      code style guides, architectural boundaries, naming conventions, scope
      limits. Without explicit constraints, agents will generate code that works
      but does not fit the project.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      <strong>What the PM defines:</strong> guardrails at the product level. Which
      features are out of scope for this iteration. Which third-party services are
      approved. What data the agent must never expose. Engineers define implementation-level
      constraints (type systems, linting rules, security policies); PMs define product-level
      constraints.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">Tests and Feedback</h2>
    <p>
      The agent needs a way to know if it succeeded. Without feedback loops, it
      generates code in the dark. Feedback can be automated: linting, type
      checks, unit tests, integration tests, CI pipelines. It can also be human:
      code review, product review, acceptance testing.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      <strong>What the PM defines:</strong> acceptance criteria. Not just "does the
      code compile" but "does the product do what the user needs." Defining clear,
      testable acceptance criteria is the most leveraged thing a PM can do to improve
      agent output quality.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">State and Handoff</h2>
    <p>
      AI agents do not remember what happened in a previous session unless you
      give them a way to. State must be persisted in artifacts: CLAUDE.md files,
      project documentation, structured task descriptions, Git history.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-2">
      The CLAUDE.md pattern — a project-level file that documents conventions,
      architecture decisions, and current context — is a practical example of
      harness engineering. It turns implicit knowledge into explicit context
      that the agent can read on every invocation. When work passes between team
      members or sessions, structured handoff documents serve the same purpose.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">
      What the PM Owns vs. What Requires Engineering Judgment
    </h2>
    <p>
      Harness engineering is not a replacement for engineering. It is a
      complementary discipline.
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-2 space-y-2">
      <li>
        <strong>PMs define:</strong> the product goal, acceptance criteria, scope
        boundaries, context that matters, and the definition of "done."
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Engineers define:</strong> architecture decisions, performance requirements,
        security policies, testing strategies, and implementation patterns.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>They share:</strong> the harness design. PMs bring product clarity.
        Engineers bring technical rigor. Together they create an environment where
        AI agents produce reliable, useful output.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">
      A PM who designs harnesses without engineering input builds agents that
      are product-correct but technically fragile. An engineer who builds
      harnesses without PM input creates technically sound agents that solve the
      wrong problems.
    </p>

    <h2 class="mt-6 text-xl font-semibold">
      Connection to AI PM Operating Playbook
    </h2>
    <p>
      The AI PM Operating Playbook's Coding-Agent Handoff tool operationalizes
      harness engineering. It generates structured documents that define
      context, constraints, acceptance criteria, and test expectations — the
      exact inputs an agent needs to work productively. If you are new to
      harness engineering, starting with a generated handoff is a practical way
      to see what a well-defined harness looks like.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-8 mb-8">
      <a
        href={PLAYBOOK_BASE}
        class="bg-accent text-accent-foreground inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium transition-opacity hover:opacity-90"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener noreferrer"
      >
        Generate a coding-agent handoff with AI PM Operating Playbook ↗
      </a>
    </div>

    <div class="border-border mt-8 rounded-lg border p-6">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold">Related</h2>
      <div class="mt-3 flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/loop-engineering")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Loop Engineering
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/vibe-coding")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Vibe Coding for Product Discovery
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook/agent-product-design")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Agent Product Design
        </a>
        <a
          href={getRelativeLocaleUrl(locale, "playbook")}
          class="text-accent hover:underline"
        >
          Playbook Index
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
